In its resolve to end the contention between Health Maintenance Organisations (HMOs) and Health Care Facilities (HCFs) over claims of unpaid bills, the National Health Insurance Scheme (NHIS) has embarked on a reconciliation exercise.According to the statement issued by the head, Media and Public Relations Division, NHIS, Ayo Osinlu, other objectives of the exercise include ensuring that all stakeholders abide faithfully with their obligations under the Operational Guidelines of the Scheme, as well as the restoration of full stakeholder and public confidence in NHIS. He said that the management of the Scheme, as part of the implementation of its rebranding agenda which highlights transparency and accountability in the system, had in December last year issued a public notice inviting healthcare facilities accredited by the Scheme to submit claims of unsettled bills standing against the HMOs. “This followed strident complaints by HCFs over the failure of HMOs to effect payment of bills accruing from care given to enrollees under NHIS, as well as other private insurance plans operated by HMOs. “The need to address this as an agency arises from reported cases of consequent service failure, whereby some facilities in the country are withholding care from enrollees over unpaid capitation and fee-for-service by HMOs, inspite of receiving funds timely from NHIS for those purposes. 